{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17625576","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17625576"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T16:29:29+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T16:29:29+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17038"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17038","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17038"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0,0.68,0.04,0.21,0.08]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9728"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"70408"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9728","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9728"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17038"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"55872"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4936"},{"type":"tags","id":"4943"},{"type":"tags","id":"4944"},{"type":"tags","id":"5254"},{"type":"tags","id":"5261"},{"type":"tags","id":"10824"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"22883"},{"type":"contributions","id":"23057"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"70408","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/70408"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 45-year-old woman presents to her general practitioner with a sore throat and fever. Examination reveals tonsillar exudates and tender cervical lymphadenopathy. A rapid antigen test confirms group A streptococcal infection. The doctor prescribes phenoxymethylpenicillin, explaining it belongs to the penicillin class of antibiotics that contain a characteristic beta-lactam ring structure.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the mechanism of action of penicillins?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Disrupts bacterial cell membrane permeability","Prevents peptidoglycan cross-linking","Inhibits bacterial cell wall precursor transport","Blocks bacterial cell wall protein assembly","Degrades existing bacterial cell wall components"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EPenicillins \u003Cstrong\u003Eprevent peptidoglycan cross-linking\u003C/strong\u003E in the bacterial cell wall. They bind to penicillin-binding proteins (PBPs); enzymes responsible for forming peptide bridges between peptidoglycan strands. This eventuates in bacterial cell lysis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe other, incorrect mechanisms are below:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDisrupts bacterial cell membrane permeability\u003C/strong\u003E: this mechanism is characteristic of polymyxins, which act on bacterial cell membranes. Penicillins do not primarily affect membrane permeability.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EInhibits bacterial cell wall precursor transport\u003C/strong\u003E: penicillins act at the final stage of cell wall assembly rather than affecting the transport of precursor molecules.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBlocks bacterial cell wall protein assembly\u003C/strong\u003E: penicillins specifically target peptidoglycan cross-linking rather than general protein assembly in the cell wall.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDegrades existing bacterial cell wall components\u003C/strong\u003E: penicillins prevent the formation of new cell wall rather than breaking down existing structures.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe beta-lactam ring structure of penicillins is essential as it mimics the D-alanyl-D-alanine portion of peptidoglycan, allowing it to bind to and inhibit PBPs. This structural specificity explains why beta-lactamase enzymes can inactivate penicillins by cleaving this ring.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Penicillins inhibit bacterial cell wall synthesis by binding to penicillin-binding proteins.","Beta-lactam antibiotics prevent cross-linking of peptidoglycan in the bacterial cell wall.","The beta-lactam ring structure is essential for the antimicrobial activity of penicillins."],"references":["Therapeutic Guidelines. Melbourne: Therapeutic Guidelines Limited. Available from: https://www.tg.org.au","Ritter J, Flower RJ (Rod J), Henderson G (Graeme), et al.\u00a0Rang and Dale\u2019s Pharmacology. Tenth edition. Elsevier; 2024.","Australian Medicines Handbook\u00a0(online). Adelaide: Australian Medicines Handbook Pty Ltd. Available from:\u00a0https://amhonline.amh.net.au/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"55872"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17038"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"55872","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/55872"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-14T22:38:06+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-14T22:39:14+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9728"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"70408"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pr